:"text","url":"/integrations/web-ui#publishing-maintainers","content":"Publish hyper-pm first, then hyper-pm-web, using pnpm publish from each app so workspace: ranges rewrite correctly. Details in apps/hyper-pm-web/README.md."},"779":{"id":"/integrations/web-ui-58","page_id":"/integrations/web-ui","type":"text","url":"/integrations/web-ui#publishing-maintainers","content":"type: info"},"780":{"id":"/integrations/web-ui-59","page_id":"/integrations/web-ui","type":"text","url":"/integrations/web-ui#publishing-maintainers","content":"For terminal-first workflows and every CLI flag in one place, see Examples and the CLI reference."},"781":{"id":"/intro/architecture","page_id":"/intro/architecture","type":"page","content":"Architecture","url":"/intro/architecture"},"782":{"id":"/intro/architecture-0","page_id":"/intro/architecture","type":"text","url":"/intro/architecture","content":"How the data branch, JSONL log, worktrees, and projections fit together."},"783":{"id":"/intro/architecture-1","page_id":"/intro/architecture","type":"heading","url":"/intro/architecture#high-level-flow","content":"High-level flow"},"784":{"id":"/intro/architecture-2","page_id":"/intro/architecture","type":"heading","url":"/intro/architecture#repository-layout-conceptual","content":"Repository layout (conceptual)"},"785":{"id":"/intro/architecture-3","page_id":"/intro/architecture","type":"heading","url":"/intro/architecture#event-sourcing-mindset","content":"Event sourcing mindset"},"786":{"id":"/intro/architecture-4","page_id":"/intro/architecture","type":"heading","url":"/intro/architecture#sync-as-a-side-channel","content":"Sync as a side channel"},"787":{"id":"/intro/architecture-5","page_id":"/intro/architecture","type":"heading","url":"/intro/architecture#wrappers-share-one-binary","content":"Wrappers share one binary"},"788":{"id":"/intro/architecture-6","page_id":"/intro/architecture","type":"text","url":"/intro/architecture#high-level-flow","content":"init creates or adopts an orphan branch (no parent commit) that holds hyper-pm data, and writes .hyper-pm/config.json in your working tree."},"789":{"id":"/intro/architecture-7","page_id":"/intro/architecture","type":"text","url":"/intro/architecture#high-level-flow","content":"Most mutating commands run against a temporary Git worktree checked out at the data branch, append one or more lines to the event log, commit, and optionally push — your primary branch is untouched."},"790":{"id":"/intro/architecture-8","page_id":"/intro/architecture","type":"text","url":"/intro/architecture#high-level-flow","content":"Reads replay the log (with schema versioning) into an in-memory projection of epics, stories, tickets, and sync cursors."},"791":{"id":"/intro/architecture-9","page_id":"/intro/architecture","type":"text","url":"/intro/architecture#repository-layout-conceptual","content":"Exact filenames on the data branch are owned by the CLI implementation; treat them as opaque except through supported commands."},"792":{"id":"/intro/architecture-10","page_id":"/intro/architecture","type":"text","url":"/intro/architecture#event-sourcing-mindset","content":"Think of the JSONL file as an append-only journal:"},"793":{"id":"/intro/architecture-11","page_id":"/intro/architecture","type":"text","url":"/intro/architecture#event-sourcing-mindset","content":"Each line is a typed event (for example TicketCreated, GithubInboundUpdate)."},"794":{"id":"/intro/architecture-12","page_id":"/intro/architecture","type":"text","url":"/intro/architecture#event-sourcing-mindset","content":"Deleting entities is modeled as soft deletes via events, not rm on rows."},"795":{"id":"/intro/architecture-13","page_id":"/intro/architecture","type":"text","url":"/intro/architecture#event-sourcing-mindset","content":"doctor validates that the log can be read and replayed; use it in CI or before releases if you rely on automation."},"796":{"id":"/intro/architecture-14","page_id":"/intro/architecture","type":"text","url":"/intro/architecture#sync-as-a-side-channel","content":"GitHub is a projection target, not the source of truth for hyper-pm’s core model. Outbound sync updates issues; inbound sync (full mode) translates issue changes back into events when they differ from what hyper-pm last wrote."},"797":{"id":"/intro/architecture-15","page_id":"/intro/architecture","type":"text","url":"/intro/architecture#wrappers-share-one-binary","content":"hyper-pm-web and hyper-pm-mcp spawn the same bundled CLI (dist/main.cjs) that you would run in a shell. That keeps UI, agents, and scripts aligned — there is no second implementation of business rules in the web layer."},"798":{"id":"/intro/overview","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"page","content":"Overview","url":"/intro/overview"},"799":{"id":"/intro/overview-0","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview","content":"What hyper-pm is for, how it stores data in Git, and when to use GitHub sync."},"800":{"id":"/intro/overview-1","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"heading","url":"/intro/overview#what-hyper-pm-is","content":"What hyper-pm is"},"801":{"id":"/intro/overview-2","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"heading","url":"/intro/overview#what-it-is-not","content":"What it is not"},"802":{"id":"/intro/overview-3","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"heading","url":"/intro/overview#interfaces","content":"Interfaces"},"803":{"id":"/intro/overview-4","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"heading","url":"/intro/overview#optional-github-issues-sync","content":"Optional GitHub Issues sync"},"804":{"id":"/intro/overview-5","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"heading","url":"/intro/overview#ai-assisted-fields","content":"AI-assisted fields"},"805":{"id":"/intro/overview-6","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview#what-hyper-pm-is","content":"hyper-pm is a Git-native project manager: epics, stories, tickets, comments, and sync metadata live in your repository on a dedicated data branch, not only in a SaaS database. The CLI (and anything that wraps it) mutates state by appending typed events to a JSONL log and replaying them to build the current projection."},"806":{"id":"/intro/overview-7","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview#what-hyper-pm-is","content":"That design gives you:"},"807":{"id":"/intro/overview-8","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview#what-hyper-pm-is","content":"Offline-first workflows after clone and fetch — no hosted PM required for local reads and writes."},"808":{"id":"/intro/overview-9","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview#what-hyper-pm-is","content":"Reviewable history of who changed what, suitable for compliance-minded teams."},"809":{"id":"/intro/overview-10","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview#what-hyper-pm-is","content":"Disposable worktrees for mutations so your main checkout stays clean while the tool edits the data branch."},"810":{"id":"/intro/overview-11","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview#what-it-is-not","content":"A full replacement for GitHub Projects, Jira workflows, or cross-repo portfolio views out of the box."},"811":{"id":"/intro/overview-12","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview#what-it-is-not","content":"A multi-tenant hosted service: security and backups are your Git hosting and practices."},"812":{"id":"/intro/overview-13","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview#interfaces","content":"Surface"},"813":{"id":"/intro/overview-14","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview#interfaces","content":"Role"},"814":{"id":"/intro/overview-15","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview#interfaces","content":"hyper-pm CLI"},"815":{"id":"/intro/overview-16","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview#interfaces","content":"Canonical API: init, CRUD on epics/stories/tickets, work, comment, sync, audit, doctor, repo helpers."},"816":{"id":"/intro/overview-17","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview#interfaces","content":"hyper-pm-web"},"817":{"id":"/intro/overview-18","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview#interfaces","content":"Local browser UI that shells the same CLI bundle; good for browsing and editing without memorizing flags."},"818":{"id":"/intro/overview-19","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview#interfaces","content":"hyper-pm-mcp"},"819":{"id":"/intro/overview-20","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview#interfaces","content":"stdio MCP server exposing hyper_pm_run so agents can invoke the CLI with structured JSON."},"820":{"id":"/intro/overview-21","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview#interfaces","content":"type: warn"},"821":{"id":"/intro/overview-22","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview#interfaces","content":"Treat MCP and the web API as powerful local automation: only enable them in environments you trust, and prefer binding the web server to loopback unless you have auth and TLS in front."},"822":{"id":"/intro/overview-23","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview#optional-github-issues-sync","content":"When sync is enabled and credentials are present, hyper-pm can push ticket changes to GitHub Issues and, in full mode, pull inbound edits and attach PR timeline signals for tickets that are in progress and linked to issues. See GitHub sync for behavior details and limits."},"823":{"id":"/intro/overview-24","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview#ai-assisted-fields","content":"Some ticket commands support --ai-draft and --ai-improve when HYPER_PM_AI_API_KEY is set. These call out to your configured AI provider from the CLI environment — review outputs before committing them to shared tickets."}},"count":823},"sorting":{"language":"english","sortabl